System Prompt Bridge + Priority-Weighted Micro-Sleep
=====================================================
2026-03-09

Problem
-------
The model cannot answer "What's my son's name?" in chat despite the sidebar
showing recall 1.00 on the fact "Family Has a son named Andre Patandre."

Root cause: MEMIT edits the raw completion pathway. When the model sees the
raw prompt "Family Has a son named ->", the edited weights fire and produce
"Andre Patandre." But in chat, the prompt is wrapped in chat template tokens
(<|user|>, <|assistant|>, etc.) — a fundamentally different token sequence.
The MEMIT edit never activates.

The same blind spot exists for LoRA. Training data uses to_question() /
to_answer() in chat format (this was already correct), but the generated
questions don't cover all phrasings a user might ask. A fact trained as
"What does Family have?" won't necessarily answer "What's my son's name?"

Investigation also revealed that the EditLedger (JSON on disk) — not the
weight edits — is the actual source of truth for what the model knows. The
sidebar reads from the ledger, not from the weights. If the ledger were lost,
the weight edits would be invisible and unrecoverable.


The Role of Each Tier (Clarified)
----------------------------------
- Tier 0 (context window): What the model reads in the system prompt. This is
  what actually makes it answer correctly in chat. Volatile — gone on restart.

- Tier 2 (MEMIT edits): Durable store. Survives restarts (persisted to disk
  via EditLedger + delta .npz files). Provides raw completion recall for
  verification/graduation testing. Does NOT help chat directly.

- Tier 3 (LoRA fusion): Permanent. Baked into model weights. Eventually facts
  graduate here and can be removed from the system prompt to free token space.

MEMIT's essential long-term purpose: graduation verification. It's how we know
when a fact has been absorbed by LoRA and can safely be removed from the system
prompt. The raw completion test answers: "does the model know this intrinsically,
without being told?" Without it, we'd either keep every fact in the system prompt
forever (running out of token space) or remove facts blindly.


Change 1: System Prompt Bridge
-------------------------------
Files: src/wake/context.py, src/orchestrator.py

ContextManager now accepts a facts provider (callable returning List[FactTriple])
and injects known facts into the system prompt on every turn:

    You may recall things from previous conversations.

    Things you remember about the user:
    - Family Has a son named: Andre Patandre (age and occupation are unknown)
    - *Child Age: 6
    - Vladimir Name: This
    ...

The orchestrator wires edit_ledger.get_facts_for_training as the provider.
Facts are read fresh from the ledger each turn, so new MEMIT edits appear
immediately. Cost: ~200-400 tokens for 18 facts (~5-10% of 4096 context).


Change 2: Priority Scoring on Facts
-------------------------------------
Files: src/memory/memit.py (FactTriple, MemitEdit, EditLedger), src/wake/chat.py

FactTriple gains a `priority` field (0.0-1.0) set from the SurpriseEstimator's
composite score at extraction time. High-surprise facts (corrections, emphasis,
personal revelations) get higher priority. Priority persists through the ledger
and follows the fact through its entire lifecycle.

MemitEdit gains four per-fact spaced-repetition fields:
  - fact_priorities: from surprise score
  - fact_last_trained: timestamp of last LoRA training
  - fact_train_count: how many times LoRA has trained on this fact
  - fact_degrade_count: how many times recall failed after training

All backward-compatible (old ledger entries get sensible defaults).


Change 3: Priority-Weighted LoRA Training
------------------------------------------
Files: src/sleep/trainer.py, src/sleep/full_sleep.py

SleepTrainer gains prepare_weighted_training_data() which duplicates
high-priority facts in the training JSONL:
  - Priority 1.0 -> 3x repetition
  - Priority 0.5 -> 2x
  - Priority 0.0 -> 1x minimum
Examples are shuffled to avoid consecutive repetition of the same fact.

Full sleep's _consolidate() now calls train_and_fuse(weighted=True).


Change 4: Spaced Repetition
-----------------------------
Files: src/sleep/full_sleep.py, src/memory/memit.py (EditLedger)

During fact audit, degraded facts get their degrade_count incremented via
ledger.record_degrade(). After LoRA consolidation, all trained facts get
timestamps recorded via ledger.record_training().

Degraded facts get a priority boost in micro-sleep selection (score += 0.2
per degradation). Facts recently trained and passing recall are lower priority
for retraining.

Config: spaced_repetition.min_retrain_age_seconds (default 3600).


Change 5: Micro-Sleep
----------------------
Files: src/sleep/micro_sleep.py (new), src/orchestrator.py, src/wake/chat.py

A lightweight background LoRA pass triggered when a high-priority fact arrives
during wake. Instead of waiting for full sleep:

  1. Selects up to 3 high-priority facts from the ledger
  2. Generates priority-weighted training data
  3. Trains LoRA for 20 iterations (~5-10s on M3)
  4. Fuses adapter into base weights
  5. Reloads model and re-applies MEMIT edits
  6. Records training timestamps in ledger

Runs in a daemon thread — chat continues uninterrupted (backend.reload()
acquires write lock briefly, blocking inference for 1-2s during model swap).

Guards:
  - Priority must exceed threshold (default 0.7)
  - Cooldown between micro-sleeps (default 120s)
  - Won't fire during full sleep or nap
  - Full sleep won't start while micro-sleep is running

Config: micro_sleep.enabled (default false — opt-in).

Human analogy: flashbulb memory. "Remember, my son's name is Andre" triggers
immediate encoding because the surprise/emphasis signal is high. Mundane facts
("I like music") wait for regular sleep consolidation.


Lifecycle After These Changes
------------------------------

  User says something -> extract facts -> assign priority from surprise score

  Low priority (< 0.7):
    Buffer -> consolidate via MEMIT -> system prompt shows it immediately
    -> full sleep trains LoRA (1x repetition) -> graduation test over cycles

  High priority (>= 0.7):
    Buffer -> consolidate via MEMIT -> system prompt shows it immediately
    -> micro-sleep trains LoRA in background (3x repetition, 20 iters)
    -> fact may reach graduation in minutes instead of multiple sleep cycles

  Degraded facts:
    Audit detects degradation -> degrade_count++ -> priority boost
    -> micro-sleep picks them up sooner -> spaced repetition reinforcement


